> There's a reason why spaghetti and meatballs is typically a Sunday night dinner—it takes hours to make! This version uses Italian sausage as a meatball shortcut, eliminating extra prep while adding delicious flavor. Smoky paprika gives this marinara a unique kick.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Halve, peel, and finely dice the @yellow onion{1%unit}(peeled and finely diced). Peel, then finely dice the @carrots{1%unit}(peeled and finely diced).

Start the marinara: Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pan{} over medium heat. Add the carrot and onion and cook, tossing, for about ~{5%minutes}, until softened. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Meanwhile, remove the @sweet Italian pork sausage{9%ounce} from the casings; discarding the casings. Wet your fingers, then form the sausage into Tablespoon-sized meatballs. Add the @linguine{6%ounce} to the boiling water and cook for ~{9-11%minutes}, until al dente, drain.

Add the @diced tomatoes{1%box} and 1 cup water to the pan with the veggies and bring to a boil. Add @sugar{1/2%teaspoon} and half the @smoked paprika{1%teaspoon} (or more if you prefer a smokier flavor) to the pan. Season generously with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Reduce to a low simmer.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in another large pan over medium-high heat. Add the sausage meatballs to the pan and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}, rotating to brown on all sides. When finished, add them to the marinara.

Toss and serve: Add the linguine, @dried thyme{1%teaspoon}, and half the @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} to the marinara. Toss for ~{1-2%minutes}, until thoroughly combined and heated through. Serve the speedy Italian meatballs with smoked tomato linguine, garnished with the remaining parmesan cheese and enjoy!